{
  "_comment": "Hand-authored rig for examples/drawings/poptart-and-person.jpg (1400x792). TWO-FIGURE CASE: a legless pop-tart rectangle (left) and a stick person with real legs (right), drawn as two disconnected sharpie blobs. Requires figures:2 so key() keeps both blobs. The renderer puppets ONE root, so the pop-tart is root and every person part is parented to it \u2014 the two figures translate as one rigid unit, but because the renderer's transforms are FLAT (each non-root part rotates about its own pivot in root space, parenting is not hierarchical), the person's legs still swing a real gait and the pop-tart still rides along on the global bob+squash. Joke intended: the pop-tart has no legs, cannot walk, and is travelling anyway. Root pivot x=600 is a framing choice, not anatomy \u2014 root pivot x is only used to centre the scene, and 600 is the value that fits both figures in an 880px canvas. Sprinkles use `blink` rather than `spring`: a symmetric dot rotated about its own centre is visually identical, and pivoting it off-centre drags its clip window onto blank filled paper, so blink's vertical squash is the only motion this renderer can give a dot.",
